'''Mitchell Ivey''' (born February 2, 1949) is a former American international [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who was a [[backstroke]] specialist and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[gold medal]]ist.  Ivey later became a prominent college Olympic swimming coach.

He was born in [[San Jose, California]], and trained with the Santa Clara Swim Club.

Ivey participated in two Olympics as a member of the United States Olympic Team: the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] in [[Mexico City]], and the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] in [[Munich, Germany]], wining a total of three Olympic medals.<ref name=sroprofile>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Athletes, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/iv/mitch-ivey-1.html  Mitch Ivey].  Retrieved July 5, 2012.</ref>  He won a silver medal by finishing second behind [[Roland Matthes]] in the 200-meter backstroke in 1968.<ref name=sroprofile/>  He earned a gold medal as a member of the winning U.S. relay team in the 4x100-meter medley, and also a bronze medal with a third-place finish in the 200-meter backstroke at the 1972 Olympics.<ref name=sroprofile/>  As a member of the Santa Clara Swim Club, he also won three [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) United States national championships.

Ivey became a noted Olympic and college swimming coach after his own competition swimming career ended.  He served as an assistant coach for the U.S. Olympic Team in 1988, and the head coach of the [[Florida Gators swimming and diving]] team of the [[University of Florida]] from 1990 to 1993.

